'''Bence Szabolcsi''' (2 August 1899 – 21 January 1973) was a Hungarian [[music historian]]. Along with [[Ervin Major]], "he can be considered the founder of scholarly study of the history of Hungarian music, and he was primarily responsible for creating an establishment for musicology in Hungary."<ref name="Mendelsohn1994">{{cite book|author=Ezra Mendelsohn|title=Studies in Contemporary Jewry: Volume IX: Modern Jews and Their Musical Agendas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GUajKnF6OJYC&pg=PA59|year=1994|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-508617-1|page=59}}</ref>
Szabolcsi was born in [[Budapest]], the younger son of [[Miksa Szabolcsi]] (1856-1915), editor of the Hungarian Jewish weekly ''Egyenlőség''.<ref name="Patai2000">{{cite book|author=Raphael Patai|title=Journeyman in Jerusalem: Memories and Letters, 1933-1947|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IrF7ZYWMO8MC&pg=PA262|year=2000|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-0-7391-0209-1|page=262}}</ref> He studied musicology at [[Leipzig University]], gaining a doctorate in 1923 with a thesis on the Italian [[monody|monodist]] composers [[Pierro Benedetti]] and [[Claudio Sarcini]].<ref name="Laki1995">{{cite book|editor=Peter Laki|title=Bartók and His World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=12iihhdms_EC&pg=PA290|year=1995|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=0-691-00633-4|page=290}}</ref> He edited the first music dictionary in [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]], established the Department of Musicology at the [[Franz Liszt Academy of Music]] in 1951, and established the Bartók Archive in 1961.<ref name="Mendelsohn1994"/>
==Works== * ''The twilight of Ferenc Liszt'', 1956 * ''A concise history of Hungarian music'', 1964 * ''Béla Bartók : his life in pictures'', 1964 * ''A history of melody'', 1965
