{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}} {{wiktionary}} [[File:Snowshill nychthemeron clock.jpg|thumb|The Nychthemeron Clock in [[Snowshill Manor]], Gloucestershire, UK]] '''Nychthemeron''' {{IPAc-en|n|ɪ|k|ˈ|θ|ɛ|m|ər|ɒ|n}}, occasionally '''nycthemeron''' or ''nuchthemeron'' (Greek {{lang|el|νυχθήμερον}} from the words ''nykt-'' "night", and ''hemera'' "day, daytime"), is a period of 24 consecutive [[hour]]s. It is sometimes used, especially in technical literature, to avoid the ambiguity inherent in the term ''[[day]]''.
It is the period of time that a [[calendar]] normally labels with a [[calendar date|date]], although a nychthemeron simply designates a time-span that can start at any time, not just midnight.
==In other languages== Some languages have a word for 24 hours, or more loosely a day plus a night in no particular order. Unlike a calendar date, only the length is defined, with no particular start or end. Furthermore, these words are considered basic and native to these languages, so unlike "nychthemeron", they are not associated with [[jargon]].
Words for 24 hours are listed in the middle column. For comparison, the word for ''day'', in the meaning of [[daytime]], the ''sunlit state'', the opposite of night, is also listed in the rightmost column: {| class="wikitable sortable" |- ! Language !! 24 hours !! sunlit state |- | [[Danish language|Danish]] || døgn || dag |- | Norwegian ([[Bokmål]]) || døgn || dag |- | Norwegian ([[Nynorsk]]) || døgn, døger || dag |- | [[Swedish language|Swedish]] || dygn || dag |- | [[Icelandic language|Icelandic]] || sólarhringur ("sun-circle") || dagur |- | [[Faroese language|Faroese]] || samdøgur || dagur |- |[[Old Norse]] |dǿgr, dǿgn |dagr |- | [[North Frisian language|North Frisian]] || eetlem || däi |- | [[West Frisian language|West Frisian]] || etmel || dei |- | [[Dutch language|Dutch]] || etmaal || dag |- | [[Esperanto]] || diurno,<ref name="ReVoDiurno">[http://purl.org/net/voko/revo/art/diurn.html#diurn.0o.KAL diurn/o] in [[Reta Vortaro]]</ref> tagnokto<ref name="ReVoTagnokto">[http://purl.org/net/voko/revo/art/nokt.html#nokt.tag0o nokt/o] in Reta Vortaro</ref> ("day-night") || tago |- | [[Finnish language|Finnish]] || vuorokausi ("turn-period")|| päivä |- | [[Estonian language|Estonian]] || ööpäev ("night-day") || päev |- | [[Latvian language|Latvian]] || diennakts ("day-night") || diena |- | [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]] || para || diena |- | [[Polish language|Polish]] || doba || dzień |- | [[Russian language|Russian]] || сутки {{IPA-ru|ˈsutkʲɪ|}} || день |- | [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] || יממה || יום |- | [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] || денонощие ("day-night") || ден |- | [[Bengali language|Bengali]] || দিবারাত্রি, দিনরাত || দিন |- | [[Sanskrit language|Sanskrit]] || अहोरात्र || दिन |- | [[Tamil language|Tamil]] || நாள் || பகல் |- | [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] || доба || день |- | [[Swahili language|Swahili]] || siku || mchana |- | [[Indonesian language|Indonesian/Malay]] || hari || siang |- | [[Japanese language|Japanese]] || 日 || 昼 |- | [[Korean language|Korean]] || 일 || 낮 |}
The word ''dag'', as in the Nordic languages, is [[Etymology|etymologically]] [[cognate|the same as]] ''day'' in English.
