{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]] --> | name = Anastasios (Tasos) Athanasiadis | image = | imagesize = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_date = November, 1913 | birth_place = [[Salihli]], [[Anatolia|Asia minor]] | death_date = 21 September 2006 (aged 92) | death_place = [[Athens]], [[Greece]] | occupation = [[novelist]], [[essayist]], [[biographer]] | nationality = [[Image:Flag of Greece.svg|25px|Country flag]] [[Greece|Greek]] | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | influences = | influenced = | signature = | website = }}
'''Anastasios (Tasos) Athanasiadis''' ({{lang-el|'''Τάσος Αθανασιάδης'''}}) son of Michael ([[Salihli]] of [[Anatolia|Asia minor]], November 1913-[[Athens]], 21 September 2006) was a writer and gownsman.<ref>[http://www.greek-language.gr/greekLang/modern_greek/tools/corpora/pi/content.html?t=3,2104 Presentation of Tasos Athanasiadis in the official site of “Portal for the Greek Language” of the Center for the Greek Language (in Greek)]</ref>
==Biography== He studied law in the [[National and Kapodistrian University of Athens|University of Athens]] and practiced law in the period 1940-1945. In 1945 he got posted as Manager of the [[National Theatre of Greece]] Secretariat, and afterwards as general Manager, job that he retained until 1972. In 1994 he got nominated as honorary doctor of the School of Philosophy of the University of Athens. Greece honoured him with three National Prizes and the medal of the [[Order of the Phoenix (Greek order)|Order of the Phoenix]] and he also got honoured with the silver medal of the French Academy. He got famous from his writings '' The guards of the Achaea'' (two book novel, Academy of Athens Prize of the Urani Foundation), '' Pantheoi'' (trilogy novel in four books, Academy of Athens Prize -1961), '' The throne room'' (National novel Prize -1969), and '' The children of Niobe''. In 1986 he got elected as [[gownsman|Academy of Athens (modern)]] and serviced as president of the Urani Foundation, of the Palamas Foundation and of the İpekçi Literature Prizes.<ref>[http://www.ert-archives.gr/wpasV2/public/p01-info.aspx?titleid=546&action=mInfo&mst=00%3a00%3a00%3a00 Audiovisual archive of greek channel ERT "Interview with Tasos Athanasiadis in the ''Nikterinos Episkeptis'' broadcast"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081003175659/http://www.ert-archives.gr/wpasV2/public/p01-info.aspx?titleid=546&action=mInfo&mst=00:00:00:00 |date=3 October 2008 }}</ref> As a second language he spoke French and he was a resident of [[Athens]].
